Thank you to @DefenderOrg, @ACLU_WA, @CityAttyPeteH, @SeattlePD, @KCProsecutor, @KingCoSheriff, advocates and others for creating this program and sparking this movement.

Helping people instead of funneling them into a cycle of jail and re-arrests simply makes sense. Funding current LEAD programs and helping new states begin the program is a no-brainer. I hope that House Appropriators will strongly consider LEAD funding as they plan for FY19.

Seattle charted a path for the LEAD program, and now it has been implemented in 31 states across the nation.

We cannot arrest our way out of crises like the opioid epidemic ‚Äì we need innovative, evidence-based treatment solutions like LEAD to truly change our society.

LEAD is a pre-booking diversion program that allows law enforcement to connect low-level offenders to treatment, instead of unnecessarily putting them in the criminal justice system. LEAD pairs program participants with casework services and treatment resources.

My colleagues and I are asking the House to fund creation of a Law Enforcement Assisted Diversion (LEAD) grant program to help combat the opioid epidemic and safeguard against rampant over-incarceration.

I'm proud to support this powerful, Seattle-created program. https://t.co/QJ6L9XDpt1

NAFTA renegotiation is a chance for us to bring home a win for workers. We can boost our economy, spur job growth, and protect our environment and consumers.

These things are not at odds and we have a path to make them a reality.

President Trump came into office making big promises on negotiating deals that are good for workers‚Äî but he has not.
He‚Äôs rammed through anti-worker policies and fought for a tax scam that actually doles out tax credits to the very corporations that offshore jobs.

Congress and the American people should be privy to the process. We must create seats at the table for ALL of our interests, not just corporate interests. And we need real enforcement mechanisms to defend our workers, our safety, our environment and our jobs.
None of us here are opposed to trade‚Äîyou can‚Äôt stop it any more than you can stop migration, and we wouldn‚Äôt want to. We want to build a trade deal that works for working people.
In Mexico, too, NAFTA favoritism of corporate farming ran 1.3 million Mexican farmers out of business. NAFTA has created job loss from the Midwest to Mexico, Ohio to Oaxaca.

Corporations even benefit by using  NAFTA's investor-state dispute settlement to offshore American jobs to low wage countries. Because of liberties NAFTA affords corporate giants, 930,000 American jobs have been lost under one NAFTA program alone.
